ion of original critical essays challenges readers to accept a new term, new critical category, and new literary history for twentieth-century British literature. It takes as its primary subject the fascinating and typically neglected writing of the years of the Depression and World War II - the fiction, memoirs, criticism, and journalism of writers such as Elizabeth Bowen, Storm Jameson, William Empson, George Orwell, J. B. Priestley, Harold Heslop, T. H. White, Rebecca West, John Grierson, Margery Allingham, and Stella Gibbons. Divided into four sections: Work; Community; War; and Documents, the volume focuses on qualities that distinguish these writers' literary efforts from those of the modernists or postmodernists, elucidating the web of historical, institutional, and personal relationships that together define intermodernism.Researching, analyzing, and theorising intermodernism, this book focuses on three kinds of intermodern features in texts that are typically ignored in accounts of modernism or The Auden Generation: cultural features (intermodernists typically represent working-class and working middle-class cultures); political features (intermodernists are politically radical, 'radically eccentric'); and literary features (intermodernists are committed to non-canonical, even 'middlebrow' or 'mass' genres). To encourage future scholarship on intermodernism, the volume concludes with an appendix, 'Who Were the Intermodernists?', and a bibliography of primary and secondary sources.Key featuresPresents ten original chapters written by active and prominent scholars of mid-century British literary cultureLaunches an ambitious, long-term project that marks out a new period and style in twentieth-century literary historyBroad-ranging, treating novels, journalism, manifestos, short stories, film, poetry, memoirs, letters, and travel narratives of the interwar, war, and immediately post-World War II years  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx20th centuryxEnglisch. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBluemel, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Debra Rae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColletta, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFordham, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammill, Faye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHepburn, Allan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHubble, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLassner, Phyllis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaslen, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontefiore, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863509240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863510840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748635108423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748635108/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK